<subSubSection pageId="30" pageNumber="233" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="30.[114,647,205,443]" pageId="30" pageNumber="233">
DIAGNOSIS. — 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Borojevic &amp; Boury-Esnault &amp; Vacelet" authorityYear="2000" box="[271,377,317,341]" class="Calcarea" family="Jenkinidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leucosolenida" pageId="30" pageNumber="233" phylum="Porifera" rank="family">Jenkinidae</taxonomicName>
with a syconoid organization. The cortex is thick and is supported by giant longitudinal diactines. The choanoskeleton is reduced to the unpaired actines of the subatrial spicules and smaller distal radial diactines.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="30" pageNumber="233" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="30.[114,647,481,661]" box="[114,258,481,507]" pageId="30" pageNumber="233">DESCRIPTION</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="30.[114,647,481,661]" pageId="30" pageNumber="233">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dendy &amp; Row" authorityYear="1913" box="[114,209,512,537]" class="Calcarea" family="Jenkinidae" genus="Uteopsis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Leucosolenida" pageId="30" pageNumber="233" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[114,209,512,537]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="233">Uteopsis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is well-described and illustrated by Poléjaeff (1883). It is characterized by an inarticulate choanoskeleton and a thick cortex composed of giant longitudinal diactines and triactines.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
